3 (a).System calls required 
* open()
* read()
* write()
* close()

(b) Explain any two 
read()
* Reads data from a file into memory.
write()
* Writes data from memory into a file.

(c).PROGRAM:
#include <fcntl.h>
#include <unistd.h>
int main()
{
    int source, destination;
    char buffer[100];
    int n;

    source = open("source.txt", O_RDONLY);
    destination = creat("destination.txt", 0644);

    while((n = read(source, buffer, 100)) > 0)
    {
        write(destination, buffer, n);
    }
    close(source);
    close(destination);
    return 0;
}

4.(a)Purpose of fork() and exec() 
fork()
* Creates a new child process.
exec()
* Replaces the current process with another program.

(b) Role of wait() 
Makes the parent process wait until the child process finishes execution.

(c).PROGRAM:
#include <stdio.h>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <sys/wait.h>

int main()
{
    if(fork() == 0)
    {
        execl("/bin/ls","ls",NULL);
    }
    else
    {
        wait(NULL);
        printf("Child process completed.\n");
    }
    return 0;
}
5.(A)Importance of File Management
File management is responsible for:
* Organizing files on storage devices.
* Creating, deleting and updating files.
* Providing secure access to files.
* Efficiently managing storage space.
(b) Purpose of open() and close() 
open():
* Opens a file and returns its file descriptor.
close():
* Closes the opened file and releases system resources.
(c).PROGRAM:
#include <stdio.h>
#include <fcntl.h>
#include <unistd.h>
int main()
{
    int fd;
    char buffer[100];
    fd = open("student.txt", O_RDONLY);
    read(fd, buffer, sizeof(buffer));
    printf("%s", buffer);
    close(fd);
    return 0;
}
